\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:vandermondeIdentity"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n,$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 be non-negative integers.
 Then,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+n\\
r
\end{array}\right)=\sum_{k=0}^{r}\left(\begin{array}{c}
m\\
k
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
n\\
r-k
\end{array}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The algebraic proof is similar to the one for the special case in Proposition
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:squaredSumBinomialCoefficients"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The combinatorial argument is more illuminating and significantly less
 cumbersome.
 Consider a committee consisting of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 men and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 women.
 We want to form a subcommittee of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 members.
 Clearly the number of such subcommittes is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
m+n\\
r
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 One way to form such a committee is to consider a committee with one man
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r-1$
\end_inset

 women, or two men and 
\begin_inset Formula $r-2$
\end_inset

 women, or ...
