\begin_layout Standard
Sums like 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i_{1}+i_{2}+\ldots+i_{k}=r}$
\end_inset

 should trouble you, since it's not obvious how many terms are in such a
 sum.
 Fortunately, we have the tools we need to be able to answer such questions.
 To do so, we make an analogy with a different type of question: suppose
 you have 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 urns and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 indistinguishable balls.
 How many ways could you allocate balls to urns? William Feller's famous
 textbook on probability provided an ingenious framework to think about
 this problem: suppose you have 
\begin_inset Formula $r+1$
\end_inset

 bars and 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 stars, you could then fix two bars at two ends and put all the stars and
 remaining bars in the middle.
 The gap between bars would act as urns and the stars would be balls.
 Suppose you have four bars and ten stars, one arrangment could be like
 
\begin_inset Formula $|**|*****|**|$
\end_inset

.
 This corresponds to the solution where there are 
\begin_inset Formula $3$
\end_inset

 urns and the first urn has 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 balls, the second has 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 balls, and the last again has 2 balls.
 How many other possibilities are there? Well we can rearrange the bars
 and stars in the interior of by looking at the number of slots in the interior
 (in this case 12) and choosing the slots for either the bars or the stars
 (in this case 2 or 10).
 So the answer is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
12\\
2
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
12\\
10
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

 bars in the interior along with 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 stars, leading to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
r+k-1\\
k-1
\end{array}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{c}
r+k-1\\
r
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 ways to arrange the interior bars and stars.
 Equivalently, there are 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\begin{array}{c}
r+k-1\\
k
\end{array}\right)$
\end_inset

 ways to put 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 balls in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 urns.
