\begin_layout Standard
We can generalize the idea of derangements by considering permutations that
 don't have 
\emph on
cycles.
 
\emph default
A cycle is itself a sort of generalization of a fixed point.
 A permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on a finite set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is said to have a 
\begin_inset Formula $k-$
\end_inset

cycle if there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{k}\left(x\right)=x$
\end_inset

 where the exponent is denoting repeated composition rather than multiplication.
 Of course, here 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 represents the 
\emph on
smallest 
\emph default
positive integer such that the equality holds true.
 It should be clear that it also holds true for any 
\emph on
multiple 
\emph default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 To understand cycles in permutations, it's useful to adopt a notation for
 describing permutations that can help clarify their cyclic structure.
 This is the so called 
\emph on
cyclic notation
\emph default
.
 For example, we can write a permutation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5\right\} $
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=\left(351\right)\left(24\right)
\]

\end_inset

which basically tells us that the permutation consists of two cycles 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(351\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(24\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The cycles here are 
\emph on
ordered
\emph default
, in that the first cycle represents the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(3\right)=5,f\left(5\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(1\right)=3$
\end_inset

 and the second cycle tells us that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(2\right)=4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(4\right)=2$
\end_inset

.
 Every permutation can be decomposed into cycles, and 
\emph on
non-cyclic 
\emph default
permutations are those that consist of only the trivial cycle: for instance,
 a non-cyclic permutation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 1,2,3,4,5\right\} $
\end_inset

 would be the permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(14235\right).$
\end_inset

 Note that two cycles of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1}x_{2}\ldots x_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y_{1}y_{2}\ldots y_{k}\right)$
\end_inset

 are equivalent if there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\N$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}=f^{p}\left(x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This defines an equivalence relation (as should be clear), so we can talk
 about 
\emph on
equivalence classes
\emph default
 of cycles, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\left(x_{1}x_{2}\ldots x_{k}\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Such an equivalence class consists of exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 distinct members since 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{k}\left(x_{i}\right)=x_{i}.$
\end_inset

 Thus the total number of cycles of length 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 that can be formed out of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 fixed elements is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{k!}{k}$
\end_inset

.
 We can use this to count the total number of permutations without any cycles
 using an inclusion-exclusion argument analagous to the one used for counting
 derangements in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:numDerangements"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

