What are the total number of divisors of 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{5}5^{3}11^{4}$
\end_inset

 that are perfect squares? The prime square divisors are 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{2},5^{2},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $11^{2}$
\end_inset

, where the first and last divisors appear twice.
 Thus the first product can appear at most twice, the second at most once,
 and the third at most twice in any square divisor and so the number is
 
\begin_inset Formula $(2+1)(1+1)(2+1)=18$
\end_inset

.
 More generally, for any positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 with prime factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\prod_{i=1}^{k}p_{i}^{r_{i}}$
\end_inset

, we can decompose the product into the largest square divisor 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=\prod_{i=1}^{k}\left(p_{i}^{2}\right)^{\lfloor\frac{r_{i}}{2}\rfloor}\prod_{i=1}^{k}p_{i}^{\indicate\left\{ \lfloor\frac{r_{i}}{2}\rfloor\neq\frac{r_{i}}{2}\right\} }
\]

\end_inset

where the second product is square-free and so the number of square divisors
 is given 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{i=1}^{k}\left(\lfloor\frac{r_{i}}{2}\rfloor+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

