 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi=\left(a_{1},a_{2},\cdots,a_{2021}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a permutation of 
\begin_inset Formula $(1,2,\cdots,2021)$
\end_inset

.
 For every such permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(\pi)=\prod_{j=1}^{2021}\left(a_{j}-j\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Example
Is 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\pi\right)$
\end_inset

 always even for any permutation 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

? Yes.
 To see this, note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j=1}^{2021}\left(a_{j}-j\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{j\neq i}\left(a_{j}-j\right)=-\left(a_{i}-i\right)
\]

\end_inset

where for any 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ 1,2,\ldots,2021\right\} $
\end_inset

 the sum on the LHS has an even number of terms.
 If the terms are all odd, the sum (and therefore the RHS) is even and thus
 the product is even.
\end_layout

